## Grounding in Formal Pragmatics

This project is grounded in 70+ years of linguistic theory:

**Frege (1892)** — "On Sense and Reference"
The earliest philosophical discussion of presuppositions in definite descriptions.

**Strawson (1950)** — "On Referring"
The foundational paper. "The present King of France is bald" presupposes France has a king.

**Karttunen (1973)** — "Presuppositions of Compound Sentences"
Formalizes how presuppositions work in complex sentences and how they "filter" through logical operators.

**Stalnaker (1974)** — "Pragmatic Presuppositions"
The common ground model — presuppositions are what is assumed to be shared between speaker and hearer.

**Krifka (2015)** — Modern summary of presupposition theory
Shows how presuppositions interact with focus, negation, and quantification.

**Eckardt & Sauerland (2015)** — "The Formal Semantics and Pragmatics of Presuppositions"
Accessible overview for computational linguists.

